---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { internalHref, siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout title="craft Reference" description="User-facing reference for craft: commands, target selection, features, build scripts, lockfiles, and freestanding package workflows.">
  <section class="manual-page mx-auto px-5 pb-20 pt-14 md:px-8 md:pt-18">
    <div class="eyebrow">Package Manager</div>
    <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
      `craft`
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
      `craft` is the package manager and build orchestrator. It owns package
      discovery, workspaces, dependency resolution, `Craft.lock`, `build.rn`,
      and target execution. If the question is "which package or target should
      be built?", this is the right layer.
    </p>

    <div class="manual-callout mt-10">
      <div class="manual-kicker">Validated Surface</div>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-base">
        <li>The commands on this page were checked against the current toolchain while writing the site docs.</li>
        <li>`craft doc` requires at least one library target that emits package metadata.</li>
        <li>Freestanding linker scripts should use `b.link_script(...)`, not raw `b.link_arg("-T")` path pairs.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Package shape</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`hello/
  Craft.toml
  src/
    main.rn`}</code></pre>
      <pre class="doc-code mt-6"><code>{`[package]
name = "hello"
version = "0.1.0"
kern = "0.7.0"

[runtime]
entry = "rt"
libc = false
bundle = "std"

[[bin]]
name = "hello"
root = "src/main.rn"`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        `craft` reads `Craft.toml`, derives the selected package graph, and then
        drives `kernc` with explicit actions. `craft.rn` can normalize planning
        inputs before resolution. `build.rn` runs after resolution and can stage
        sources, tools, and link inputs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Command reference</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`craft check
craft lock
craft fetch
craft doc
craft build
craft install
craft uninstall
craft run
craft test`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`craft check` validates manifests, scripts, and source analysis without doing the final link.</li>
        <li>`craft lock` writes a deterministic `Craft.lock` for the selected package graph.</li>
        <li>`craft fetch` materializes external packages into the local `.craft` cache.</li>
        <li>`craft doc` builds native package docs and writes them under `.craft/docs` when the workspace contains a metadata-emitting library target.</li>
        <li>`craft build` executes the derived compile and link actions.</li>
        <li>`craft install` and `craft uninstall` manage built `bin` targets under `ROOT/bin`.</li>
        <li>`craft run` builds and executes one selected `bin` or `example` target.</li>
        <li>`craft test` builds and runs discovered test targets.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Common options</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`--project-path path/to/pkg-or-workspace
--profile release
--examples
--bin app
--example demo
--features tls,simd
--no-default-features
--root /tmp/install-root
--verbose
--timings`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`--project-path` selects the package root, workspace root, or a direct `Craft.toml` path.</li>
        <li>`--profile` is currently `dev` or `release`.</li>
        <li>`--examples` adds example targets to `craft build`.</li>
        <li>`--bin` selects one named binary for `run`, `install`, or `uninstall`.</li>
        <li>`--example` selects one example for `craft run`.</li>
        <li>`--features` and `--no-default-features` control the package feature set used during planning.</li>
        <li>`--root` controls where `install` and `uninstall` place binaries.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Typical workflows</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`craft check
craft build
craft run
craft test

craft build --project-path path/to/workspace --profile release
craft build --examples
craft run --example demo
craft run --bin app
craft lock
craft fetch
craft install --root /tmp/kern-install
craft uninstall --root /tmp/kern-install`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        These are the day-to-day commands most users need. The same flows were
        validated for the website docs using temporary packages under `/tmp`,
        including `run`, `test`, `lock`, `fetch`, `install`, `uninstall`, and a
        separate library package for `doc`.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>`build.rn` boundary</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`use craft.builder;

pub fn build(b: *mut builder.Builder) void {
    let path = b.copy_package_file("templates/main.rn", "src/main.rn");
    b.set_source_root(path);
}`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`build.rn` runs after resolution and may not change dependency identity or lockfile shape.</li>
        <li>Relative paths resolve from the current package root, not from the workspace root.</li>
        <li>Use it for generated sources, staged artifact files, native link inputs, and package-local linker wiring.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={internalHref("/guide/build-scripts-and-generated-sources/")}>
          Build script guide
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Freestanding package workflow</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`[runtime]
entry = "none"
libc = false
bundle = "base"`}</code></pre>
      <pre class="doc-code mt-6"><code>{`#[export_name("_start")]
fn kmain() void {
    for (;;) {}
    @unreachable();
}`}</code></pre>
      <pre class="doc-code mt-6"><code>{`use craft.builder;

pub fn build(b: *mut builder.Builder) void {
    b.link_script("kernel.ld");
}`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`entry = "none"` means the package owns `_start` and there is no required program `main`.</li>
        <li>`link_script("kernel.ld")` resolves from the package root, checks that the script exists, and injects the correct linker arguments.</li>
        <li>If you need raw linker control for other cases, keep using `link_arg(...)` explicitly.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={internalHref("/guide/freestanding-and-linking/")}>
          Freestanding guide
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>When not to use `craft`</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        Drop to `kernc` when you want one explicit compile or link command
        without package discovery or workspace planning. `craft` is the right
        tool for packages. `kernc` is the right tool for single driver actions.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={internalHref("/reference/kernc")}>
          Open `kernc` reference
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Maintainer deep dive</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        If you are working on the toolchain itself rather than just using it,
        the repository still keeps lower-level `craft` internals.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/craft.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Open maintainer doc
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={internalHref("/reference")}>
          Back to reference tracks
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
